The Sense of Coherence scale

The iBerry cohort uses the 13-item version of Antonovskys Sense of Coherence (SOC) scale. Usually responses are scored on a five response options Likert scale, but iBerry has modified it to use three response options instead.

A total score is usually created from all 13 items, that is how Antonovsky argued. Despite the prescription to only use a total score, the concept of SOC is said to consist of three underlying subfactors that load onto the total score factor. Those subfactors correspond to:

  • Comprehensibility (consist items: 2, 6, 8, 9, and 11);
  • Manageability (items: 3, 5, 10, and 13);
  • Meaningfulness (items: 1, 4, 7, and 12)

Load data

There is full Sense of Coherence data available for 562 participants

df_soc <- 
  read_rds("bin/data_cleaned.rds") %>% 
  select(soc_1:soc_13) %>% 
  drop_na()

Item names by extracting the attributes of each column (the variable labels from SPSS)

Label attributes are extracted via attribute(df[[col_name]])$label

# Load SPSS file
df_spss <- 
  haven::read_spss("bin/soc.sav") %>% 
  janitor::clean_names()

df_labels <-
  # Create a tibble with the SOC item column names
  tibble(item = names(df_soc)) %>% 
  # Extract the attribute of each column name in the tibble
  mutate(label = map_chr(item, ~attributes(df_spss[[.]])$label),
         label = str_remove(label, "\\d+[.] "),
         subfactor = c("Me", "C", "Ma", "Me", "Ma", "C", "Me", "C", "C", "Ma", "C", "Me", "Ma"),
         subfactor = case_when(subfactor == "Me" ~ "Meaningfulness",
                               subfactor == "Ma" ~ "Manageability",
                               subfactor == "C" ~ "Comprehensibility"))

Descriptives

The raw correlations between all items visualized as a network. The colours correposond to the subfactors as identified by Antonovsky, the author of the SOC scale. All items should positively correlate with each other as they do here indicated by all green connections (no red/negative assocations)

mean_corr <- 
  cor(df_soc) %>% 
  qgraph::mat2vec() %>% 
  mean()

qgraph::qgraph(cor(df_soc),
               nodeNames = str_wrap(df_labels$label, width = 60, exdent = 8.5),
               groups = df_labels$subfactor, palette = "ggplot2",
               legend.cex = .38, legend.mode = "style2",
               GLratio = 1, vsize = 6.5, esize = 5,
               layout = "spring",
               borders = F, curve = .25, curveAll = T,
               title = paste("Mean correlation between items is", round_trail(mean_corr)),
               title.cex = 1.3)

Confirmatory factor analysis of one factor solution

Below is the code to test the one factor solution proposed by Antonovsky. At the bottom is a formatted table with the results of these analyses.

Fit model and extract estimates

# Set formula with all items
SOC_formula <- paste0("SOC =~ ", paste(names(df_soc), collapse = " + "))

# Fit model
cfa_fit <- cfa(
    SOC_formula,
    data = df_soc,
    std.lv = T,
    ordered = T,
    estimator = "WLSMV")

# Extract summary
df_cfa_summary <-
  summary(cfa_fit, fit.measures = T)$fit %>%
    as_tibble(rownames = "index") %>%
    mutate(value = round(value, 3)) %>%
    filter(index %in% c("rmsea", "rmsea.ci.lower", "rmsea.ci.upper",
                        "cfi", "pvalue")) %>%
    pivot_wider(values_from = "value", names_from = "index") 

# Extract loadings
df_cfa_loadings <-
  summary(cfa_fit, fit.measures = T)$pe %>% 
  transmute(Item = rhs,
         `Factor loading` = round(est, 2),
         `Standard error` = round(se, 2),
         `p-value` = round(pvalue, 3)) %>% 
  slice(1:13) %>% 
  left_join(df_labels, by = c("Item" = "item")) %>%
  arrange(`Factor loading`) %>% 
  select(Item, Label = label, `Factor loading`:`p-value`)

Reliability estimates

Cronbachs alpha

alpha_point_est <- psych::alpha(df_soc)$total$std.alpha
  
df_alpha <- 
  psych::alpha.ci(alpha_point_est, n.obs = nrow(df_soc)) %>% 
  reshape2::melt() %>% 
  filter(L1 == "lower.ci" | L1 == "upper.ci" | L1 == "alpha") %>%
  pivot_wider(values_from = "value", names_from = "L1") %>% 
  relocate(alpha)

Exploratory analysis

Below is the code to test whether different methods propose that there are more factors or components in the SOC data.

Simple eigenvalues

vec_eigen <- eigen(cor(df_soc))$values

tibble(num_eigen = 1:length(vec_eigen),
       eigen_value = vec_eigen) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = num_eigen, y = eigen_value)) +
  geom_point(size = 4, shape = 5, alpha = .8, color = "blue") +
  geom_line(aes(group = 1), size = 1.5, alpha = 1/2, linetype = 2, color = "blue") +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 1, size = 1.3,
             color = "red2", alpha = 1/4) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = 1:13) +
  labs(x = "Number of Eigenvalues", y = "Value\n") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(panel.grid.minor = element_blank())

Suggests 3 principle components.

Parallel analysis

psych::fa.parallel(df_soc)

Parallel analysis suggests that the number of factors =  5  and the number of components =  2

Exploratory factor analysis

Below I try a 3-factor solution instead of the 1-factor originally suggested.

fit_3f <- psych::fa(df_soc, nfactors = 3, rotate = "varimax") 

summary(fit_3f)

We see that the there are several items (e.g.soc_1, soc_5, soc_11) that load equally well on any of the 3 factors. This poor discrimination does not speak well for using such a structure.

Goodness of fit

Regardless, it should be noted the three-factor structure was generally a better fit for the data than the 1 factor one, as can be seen by the ANOVA comparison below:

anova(cfa_fit, fit_3f)

Hierarchical factor analysis

The code below is an attempt to fit a structure where the 3 subfactors load onto a higher order single latent factor. This is by all means an overkill considering prior results.

soc_hierarch_formula <- "
SOC_CO =~ soc_2 + soc_6 + soc_8 + soc_9 + soc_11
SOC_MA =~ soc_3 + soc_5 + soc_10 + soc_13
SOC_ME =~ soc_1 + soc_4 + soc_7 + soc_12
SOC_total =~ SOC_CO + SOC_MA + SOC_ME
"

hierarch_fit <- lavaan::sem(soc_hierarch_formula, data = df_soc)

hierarch_summ <-
  summary(hierarch_fit, fit.measures = T)$fit %>% 
  as_tibble(rownames = "index") %>%
  mutate(value = round(value, 3)) %>%
  filter(index %in% c("rmsea", "rmsea.ci.lower", "rmsea.ci.upper",
                      "cfi", "pvalue")) %>%
  pivot_wider(values_from = "value", names_from = "index")

Summary fit measures:

hierarch_summ %>% 
  transmute(CFI = cfi,
            `RMSEA [95%CI]` = paste0(rmsea, " [", rmsea.ci.lower, ", ",
                                     rmsea.ci.upper, "]"),
            `p-value` = pvalue) %>% 
  gt::gt()
